inks":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2494"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2494"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64462"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1792"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"9664"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27094"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44353"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79110"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a generalised erythematous rash, which has been developing and progressive over the past two days. He describes a fever and some minor joint pain preceding the onset of the rash. He denies any past medication history and denies taking any medications recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient has an erythematous rash, predominantly across his trunk and upper limbs. There are many typical and atypical target lesions within the rash. There are some superficial erosions on the mucosal surface of his lips and ulcers in the right buccal mucosa, as well as a crop of vesicles on his right lower lip. There is no eye involvement, and he denies genital involvement and declines genital examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative agent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Herpes simplex virus","Impetigo","Dengue virus","Varicella zoster virus","Human immunodeficiency virus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EErythema multiforme (EM) is thought to be a delayed hypersensitivity reaction. 90% of cases of EM are associated with infection. The most common causative infection is \u003Cstrong\u003Eherpes simplex virus\u003C/strong\u003E, usually HSV1 affecting the lip. The presence of target lesions and vesicles on the lip in this patient strongly suggests HSV as the causative agent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpetigo\u003C/strong\u003E is a bacterial skin infection that typically presents with honey-coloured crusts, not target lesions or mucosal involvement, making it an unlikely cause in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDengue virus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a rash, but it is usually associated with systemic symptoms like severe headache, retro-orbital pain, and myalgia, rather than target lesions or mucosal involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricella zoster virus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause vesicular rashes, but these are typically more widespread and not associated with target lesions. It also usually presents with a more distinct prodrome and distribution pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman immunodeficiency virus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause various skin manifestations, but it is not typically associated with the acute presentation of target lesions seen in erythema multiforme.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELess than 10% of EM cases are associated with medications. Treatment is targeted at the possible cause of EM, and symptomatic treatment can include topical corticosteroids, antihistamines, and anaesthetic mouthwashes. Prognosis of EM is usually good, as it is a self-limiting condition that resolves without complications. Recurrent EM can occur, especially when associated with HSV.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erythema multiforme is a clinical diagnosis - one should suspect EM if multiple target lesions are present.","The vast majority of erythema multiforme cases are triggered by infection, most commonly HSV1."],"references":["Lerch M, Mainetti C, Terziroli Beretta-Piccoli B, Harr T. Current Perspectives on Erythema Multiforme. Clin Rev Allergy Immunol. 2018 Feb;54(1):177-184. doi: 10.1007/s12016-017-8667-7. PMID: 29352387. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29352387/","Hafsi W, Badri T. Erythema Multiforme. [Updated 2024 Oct 29]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470259/","Shinde SB, Lohe V, Mohod S. Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV)-Induced Erythema Multiforme: A Rare Case Report. Cureus. 2024 Jun 18;16(6):e62650. doi: 10.7759/cureus.62650. PMID: 39036174; PMCID: PMC11258955.  Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39036174/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64462"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2494"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64462"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T15:04:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T15:06:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2494"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79110"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{